equidem, so A, the other MSS. quidem. Equidem is compounded of the particle e, which we also find in ecastor and edepol. It does not stand for ego quidem, and is sometimes found with the second or third person, though more common with the first. cf. Eun. 956 atque equidem orante, ut ne id faceret, Thaide. Ritschl expressed a strong opinion (Prol. 76 sqq.) that it was only used with the first person in Plautus, but has since retracted; see his note on Pl. Trin. 352, published at Leipsic, 1871.
